Assuming you're writing a **plain unit test** (not `@WebMvcTest`) for `SalesPointController`, you'll typically need:

```java
import com.bnpp.pf.arthur.core.controller.SalesPointController;
import com.bnpp.pf.arthur.core.model.UserSession;
import com.bnpp.pf.arthur.core.model.SalesPoint;
import com.bnpp.pf.arthur.core.service.AuthService;
import com.bnpp.pf.arthur.core.service.RedisSessionService;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.BeforeEach;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.extension.ExtendWith;

import org.mockito.InjectMocks;
import org.mockito.Mock;
import org.mockito.junit.jupiter.MockitoExtension;

import org.springframework.web.servlet.ModelAndView;

import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.List;

import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;
import static org.mockito.ArgumentMatchers.anyString;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.when;
```

And at the class level:

```java
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
class SalesPointControllerTest {
```

Mocks:

```java
@Mock
private AuthService authService;

@Mock
private RedisSessionService redisSessionService;

@InjectMocks
private SalesPointController controller;
```

No `@SpringBootTest`, no `@WebMvcTest`, and no `MockMvc` are needed for the tests I provided because we're calling the controller methods directly.

